<subSubSection id="C34D655F0702FFDEFD38FC72FC97AEF4" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="8BE836D40702FFDEFD38FC72FB03A9D8" blockId="4.[734,1152,944,971]" box="[734,1152,944,971]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">
<heading id="D0A081B80702FFDEFD38FC72FB03A9D8" box="[734,1152,944,971]" centered="true" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" reason="2">
<taxonomicName id="4C574D570702FFDEFD38FC72FB03A9D8" authority="Mortensen, 1909" authorityName="Mortensen" authorityYear="1909" box="[734,1152,944,971]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Diademaceae" genus="Diadema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pleosporales" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="ascensionis">
<emphasis id="B923EAC60702FFDEFD38FC72FC3DA9D9" bold="true" box="[734,958,944,971]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">Diadema ascensionis</emphasis>
Mortensen, 1909
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE836D40702FFDEFD43FC32FC97AEF4" blockId="4.[677,1210,1008,1700]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">
Specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C574D570702FFDEFCD7FC33FC39AE19" authorityName="Mortensen" authorityYear="1909" box="[817,954,1009,1034]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Diademaceae" genus="Diadema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pleosporales" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="ascensionis">
<emphasis id="B923EAC60702FFDEFCD7FC33FC39AE19" box="[817,954,1009,1034]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">D. ascensionis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
examined in this investigation were collected from the South Atlantic islands of 
<collectingCountry id="F34076440702FFDEFD26FBEDFC50AE5A" box="[704,979,1071,1097]" name="Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">Ascension and St. Helena</collectingCountry>
. Adult specimens had a mean horizontal test diameter of 
<quantity id="4CAF9B310702FFDEFBC7FB8DFBF3AE7A" box="[1057,1136,1103,1129]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" unit="mm" value="70.0">70 mm</quantity>
(SD ± 
<quantity id="4CAF9B310702FFDEFD43FBACFD78AE9A" box="[677,763,1134,1161]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.2" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" unit="mm" value="5.2">5.2 mm</quantity>
) and a vertical diameter of 
<quantity id="4CAF9B310702FFDEFBC4FBADFBF2AE9A" box="[1058,1137,1135,1161]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" unit="mm" value="40.0">40 mm</quantity>
(SD ± 
<quantity id="4CAF9B310702FFDEFD43FB4CFD79AEBA" box="[677,762,1166,1193]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.4" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" unit="mm" value="3.4">3.4 mm</quantity>
). Maximum test diameters of 
<quantity id="4CAF9B310702FFDEFBCAFB4CFBFAAEBA" box="[1068,1145,1166,1193]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.4" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" unit="mm" value="84.0">84 mm</quantity>
(h.d.) and 
<quantity id="4CAF9B310702FFDEFD32FB6CFCA7AEDB" box="[724,804,1198,1224]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.6" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" unit="mm" value="46.0">46 mm</quantity>
(v.d.) were found from 
<specimenCount id="9D51FD5D0702FFDEFBCEFB6CFB39AEDB" box="[1064,1210,1198,1224]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" type="generic">28 specimens</specimenCount>
examined.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34D655F0702FFDFFD5DFB2CFE01A99F" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="98" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BE836D40702FFDEFD5DFB2CFCCBAC57" blockId="4.[677,1210,1008,1700]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">
Test colour was black, commonly with a red tinge. This was more noticeable in juvenile specimens. The same pattern of iridophores occurred in this species as in 
<taxonomicName id="4C574D570702FFDEFC90FA8FFB8BAF75" authorityName="Philippi" authorityYear="1845" box="[886,1032,1356,1382]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Diademaceae" genus="Diadema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pleosporales" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="antillarum">
<emphasis id="B923EAC60702FFDEFC90FA8FFB8BAF75" box="[886,1032,1356,1382]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">D. antillarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C574D570702FFDEFBD8FA8FFB31AF75" authorityName="Michelin" authorityYear="1845" box="[1086,1202,1357,1382]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Diademaceae" genus="Diadema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pleosporales" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="savignyi">
<emphasis id="B923EAC60702FFDEFBD8FA8FFB31AF75" box="[1086,1202,1357,1382]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">D. savignyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with lines of iridophores down the mid-lines of the interambulacra and a ring around the apical system. This feature was not as obvious as in the afore-mentioned species. White dots were present on the naked median areas of the interambulacra, being more obvious at night, not always visible during the day.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE836D40702FFDFFD5DF988FDDBAB01" blockId="4.[677,1210,1008,1700]" lastBlockId="5.[113,647,216,908]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="98" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">
The shape of the test was very similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C574D570702FFDEFD43F9A8FCBAAC90" authorityName="Philippi" authorityYear="1845" box="[677,825,1641,1667]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Diademaceae" genus="Diadema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pleosporales" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="antillarum">
<emphasis id="B923EAC60702FFDEFD43F9A8FCBAAC90" box="[677,825,1641,1667]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">D. antillarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The ambulacra measured 25-30% of the width of the interambulacra measured at the ambitus and as reported by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC64B250703FFDFFE27FF1AFD05AAE1" author="MORTENSEN T." box="[449,646,216,242]" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" refId="ref9794" refString="MORTENSEN T. 1940. - Monograph of the Echinoidea. III (1). C. A. Reitzel, Copenhagen, 370 p." type="book" year="1940">Mortensen (1940)</bibRefCitation>
showed no variation to that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C574D570703FFDFFE58FF3AFDD2AB02" authorityName="Philippi" authorityYear="1845" box="[446,593,247,273]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Diademaceae" genus="Diadema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pleosporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="antillarum">
<emphasis id="B923EAC60703FFDFFE58FF3AFDD2AB02" box="[446,593,247,273]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">D. antillarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE836D40703FFDFFF6EFED5FF57A8BD" blockId="5.[113,647,216,908]" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">
The apical system (
<figureCitation id="136C2A510703FFDFFEB8FED5FE32AB22" box="[350,433,279,305]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="4.[113,124,680,697]" captionTargetBox="[171,1160,218,635]" captionTargetId="figure-23@4.[134,1189,203,645]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIG. 1. — Drawings of the apical systems, showing species specific characters of the periproct and genital plates: A, Diadema antillarum; B, D. ascensionis; C, D. mexicanum; D, D. palmeri; E, D. paucispinum; F, D. savignyi; G, D. setosum; H, Echinothrix calamaris (brown colour morph); I, E. calamaris (white colour morph); J, E. diadema. Scale bars: 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5401708" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5401708/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
) was distinctly depressed, hemicyclic and measured 20-26% (h.d.) in adults, a slightly larger percentage of the test’s horizontal diameter in juveniles. The periproct measured 12-18% (h.d.), with a small black anal cone with no distinguishing features. Both the apical system and the corresponding periproct tended to be larger in this species than in 
<taxonomicName id="4C574D570703FFDFFE0DFE34FDFCA81C" authorityName="Philippi" authorityYear="1845" box="[491,639,501,527]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Diademaceae" genus="Diadema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pleosporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="antillarum">
<emphasis id="B923EAC60703FFDFFE0DFE34FDFCA81C" box="[491,639,501,527]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">D. antillarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The genital plates (
<figureCitation id="136C2A510703FFDFFEA1FDD7FE18A83C" box="[327,411,533,559]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="4.[113,124,680,697]" captionTargetBox="[171,1160,218,635]" captionTargetId="figure-23@4.[134,1189,203,645]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIG. 1. — Drawings of the apical systems, showing species specific characters of the periproct and genital plates: A, Diadema antillarum; B, D. ascensionis; C, D. mexicanum; D, D. palmeri; E, D. paucispinum; F, D. savignyi; G, D. setosum; H, Echinothrix calamaris (brown colour morph); I, E. calamaris (white colour morph); J, E. diadema. Scale bars: 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5401708" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5401708/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
) had fewer tubercles (between zero and two) than 
<taxonomicName id="4C574D570703FFDFFE54FDF7FDC4A85D" authorityName="Philippi" authorityYear="1845" box="[434,583,564,590]" class="Dothideomycetes" family="Diademaceae" genus="Diadema" kingdom="Fungi" order="Pleosporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="98" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="antillarum">
<emphasis id="B923EAC60703FFDFFE54FDF7FDC4A85D" box="[434,583,564,590]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">D. antillarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with distinct arched depressions seen on the denuded tests of juveniles. These markings tended to fade with age.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE836D40703FFDFFF6EFD71FEE1A95F" blockId="5.[113,647,216,908]" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">The mid-lines of the interambulacra on the naked test had no obvious markings. On living specimens, thin lines of iridophores were found in these areas. These lines bisected the naked median “spot” areas of the interambulacra.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE836D40703FFDFFF6EFC93FE01A99F" blockId="5.[113,647,216,908]" pageId="5" pageNumber="98">The peristome was black with a purple tinge and measured 40-50% (h.d.).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
